Class Table

  • java.lang.Object
    • poker.model.logic.Table

  • public class Table
extends java.lang.Object
    Represents one Tournament, i.e. a sequence of hands until a player has won all chips.

    • Constructor Detail

      • Table

        public Table(AbstractPlayer[] players,
     boolean updateGui)
        Constructor using default values for Stack Size, Start Blind and Number of Hands until increasing Blinds.

        Creates a new Tournament/Table and waits for a call to run(). The dealer position is randomly chosen.
        Parameters:
        players - An array of players that participate at the tournament.
        updateGui - Should the GUI be updated?
        See Also:
        Table(AbstractPlayer[], int, int, int, boolean)

      • Table

        public Table(AbstractPlayer[] players,
     int startStack,
     int startBlind,
     int increaseBlind,
     boolean updateGui)
        Constructor with maximal flexibility.

        Creates a new Tournament/Table and waits for a call to run(). The dealer position is randomly chosen.
        Parameters:
        players - An array of players that participate at the tournament.
        startStack - The initial stack of each player.
        startBlind - The size of the first blind.
        increaseBlind - The number of hands to play before increasing blinds.
        updateGui - Should the GUI be updated?

      • run

        public void run()
        Main loop for one tournament.

        This is the sequence for one tournament:
        • Call each player's tableStarted(...) along with its position at the table
        • While: There are at least two players left with chips
        • Do: Call the playHand() method!
        • Call each player's tableFinished(...)
        See Also:
        AbstractPlayer, playHand()

      • playHand

        public void playHand()
        Main loop for one hand.

        This is the sequence for one hand:
        • Call each player's handStarted(...)
        • While: The hand isn't finished (e.g. a betting round isn't finished yet)
        • Do: Consecutively request the player's actions by calling getAction(...)
        • Call each player's handFinished(...)
        See Also:
        AbstractPlayer
